        "contentData": [
          {
            "contentTypeKey": "cc37be6c-af82-4a8f-bcfe-5dc50d675c4f",
            "udi": "umb://element/ffd28c0c34ec417d80a6a5d733660714",
            "question": "Applicants with variable pay or non standard income",
            "answer": {
              "layout": {
                "Umbraco.BlockList": [
                  {
                    "contentUdi": "umb://element/38e93ef26eb44e53a2451a72f0821ca5"
                  }
                ]
              },
              "contentData": [
                {
                  "contentTypeKey": "dba6735d-7dc0-4fe4-b679-bb35d308181a",
                  "udi": "umb://element/38e93ef26eb44e53a2451a72f0821ca5",
                  "answer": "<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £1,800,000 at 75% LTV </strong></span><strong><span class=\"-blue-text\">            </span>        </strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicant held a senior position in a large bank and was <strong>paid a large salary as well as bonuses</strong>. The size of loan they wanted wouldn’t have been possible under our standard loan terms.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">When reviewing the case we were happy to include the <strong>average of 100% of their bonuses for the previous two years</strong> as part of the total assessable income, even though the <strong>bonuses varied each year</strong>. This was due to the <strong>applicant’s track record of bonuses </strong>at a similar level in previous years, <strong>demonstrating a sustainable source of income</strong>.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong><span class=\"list-bullets\">Application for loan of £391,500</span> at 90% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicant was in a role that <strong>paid an insufficient income (excluding bonuses)</strong> to secure the loan size they wanted under our standard terms.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">When reviewing the case we could see the applicant was able to <strong>evidence a track record of receiving bonuses</strong> and we were satisfied that the <strong>bonuses would continue to be earnt</strong>. Therefore we were able to include the <strong>average of 100% of their bonuses during the previous two years</strong> as part of the total assessable income, even though the bonuses varied each year.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £380,000 at 50% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicants were <strong>joint owners of a limited company but their household income was slightly less than required</strong> for our standard affordability assessment, due to the need for a <strong>short mortgage term</strong></span><strong>on a capital and interest basis</strong><strong>.</strong></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">When reviewing the case we could see the applicants both had an undrawn Self Invested Personal Pension (SIPP). By providing us with <strong>evidence of the SIPP balances</strong> we were able to include these as part of the total assessable income, even though the<strong> SIPPs hadn’t moved into income drawdown</strong>.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £265,000 at 70% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicant was in a role that paid an <strong>income (excluding overtime) that wouldn’t have been enough</strong> to secure the loan size they wanted under our standard terms.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">When reviewing the case we could see evidence of a <strong>track record of overtime payments, </strong>and were satisfied that it <strong>would be ongoing, </strong>meaning we were able to <strong>include this at 100% of their average income.</strong></span></li>\n</ul>"
                }
              ],
              "settingsData": []
            }
          },
          {
            "contentTypeKey": "cc37be6c-af82-4a8f-bcfe-5dc50d675c4f",
            "udi": "umb://element/fb0eb9fb46704b93ab8b05c7032e2ccf",
            "question": "Self employed applicants with only evidence of last year’s accounts",
            "answer": {
              "layout": {
                "Umbraco.BlockList": [
                  {
                    "contentUdi": "umb://element/e168cb401f7b4f44a46ab62809357aa0"
                  }
                ]
              },
              "contentData": [
                {
                  "contentTypeKey": "dba6735d-7dc0-4fe4-b679-bb35d308181a",
                  "udi": "umb://element/e168cb401f7b4f44a46ab62809357aa0",
                  "answer": "<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £1,249,500 at 85% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">One of the applicants has only<strong> recently become self employed; less than two years ago</strong>. Their company is in the same industry they had previously been employed in. With this employment history they wouldn’t have been able to secure the loan on standard terms.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">When reviewing the case they were able to provide <strong>evidence that the company was performing well</strong>, even though it was relatively new. This <strong>included one years’ finalised accounts and the latest year’s net profit after tax (NPAT) and salary</strong>. On standard terms we would normally require evidence of dividends being received.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">We therefore used <strong>one year’s finalised accounts and the latest year’s NPAT and salary</strong> for our income assessment to achieve the loan amount required.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £922,500 at 70% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicant’s company’s <strong>previous year’s profits were slightly lower than normal</strong>. With this recent dip in profits they wouldn’t have been able to secure the loan on standard terms.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">When reviewing the case we were able to obtain <strong>evidence that the current year was on track to be equivalent to other normal years’ profits</strong>. The applicant was also able to give an <strong>acceptable reason for the one-off fall in profits</strong>.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">We therefore used the <strong>latest year’s net profit after tax (NPAT) and salary</strong> for our income assessment to achieve the loan amount required.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £335,000 at 81% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicant had only <strong>recently qualified as a Barrister</strong>. Being <strong>self employed and receiving an income that grows year on year</strong>, on standard terms the average income wouldn’t be enough to secure the loan they wanted.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">We only requested the <strong>latest year’s profit figure</strong> to be included in the application, because we also received documents to support that this <strong>level of profit would be ongoing</strong>.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">When reviewing the case we were able to use <strong>latest year’s profit figure in isolation</strong> for our income assessment, alongside the other supporting documents.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">Also, due to the <strong>high quality of the application</strong> as a whole we were able to apply a <strong>loan to income multiple of 5x their latest year's profit figure</strong>. A multiple not available on standard terms.</span></li>\n</ul>"
                }
              ],
              "settingsData": []
            }
          },
          {
            "contentTypeKey": "cc37be6c-af82-4a8f-bcfe-5dc50d675c4f",
            "udi": "umb://element/c0a6914d7ca34f9e850a32dea6eb5eff",
            "question": "Applicants who are contractors",
            "answer": {
              "layout": {
                "Umbraco.BlockList": [
                  {
                    "contentUdi": "umb://element/b9307e38fcc94aca9d52f8dd4482a3f0"
                  }
                ]
              },
              "contentData": [
                {
                  "contentTypeKey": "dba6735d-7dc0-4fe4-b679-bb35d308181a",
                  "udi": "umb://element/b9307e38fcc94aca9d52f8dd4482a3f0",
                  "answer": "<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £605,000 at 85% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicant had been working as an <strong>umbrella contractor for less than 12 months</strong> but had experience and employment history of working in the same industry.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">We assessed the income by using the <strong>average of the last 3 months payslips after the umbrella deductions</strong> (umbrella margin, apprenticeship levy, employer NICs) along with the contract.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £272,000 at 85% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">Two applicants recently <strong>returned to the UK after a period living abroad</strong>. One of them continued on an employed basis with their current employer but the other <strong>began working for their employer as a contractor</strong>. The role was fundamentally the same but on a day rate basis rather than the usual employed terms. This <strong>short length of time contracting</strong> doesn’t fit within our usual criteria, meaning on standard terms they wouldn’t be able to secure the loan they wanted.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">When reviewing the case we were satisfied that although one of the applicants was technically new to contracting their<strong> track record was sufficient</strong>. Also, even though they <strong>didn’t have a three year UK residential address history</strong>, as their credit score was good we were happy for their application to proceed.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £585,000 at 90% LTV</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">Both applicants were on <strong>skilled worker visas and had lived in the UK for three and a half years</strong>. Applicant one had been an IT contractor for two years on a day rate of £600 (£156,000 gross per annum) and applicant two was employed on a basic salary of £63,500.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">As they had a <strong>good track record in the industries they worked in, affordability was excellent and the LTI was only 3.1x</strong> we were <strong>happy to apply an exception and proceed at 90% LTV.</strong> On standard criteria the LTV is capped at 75% for skilled worker visas.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £747,000 at 90% LTV</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicant had been a <strong>contractor for 10 years and had just returned to contracting after a seven month gap </strong>whilst on maternity leave. During the gap the applicant had lived off their savings.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">As the applicant had a <strong>good track record of contracting and the current contract had a similar day rate prior to the gap</strong>, we were <strong>happy to proceed with the loan requested</strong>.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £342,000 at 90% LTV</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">Applicant one had worked in the TV and film industry for two years, <strong>working on multiple projects, all of which were on a contract basis and paid via PAYE</strong>. Applicant two was employed full time in a permanent position.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">We were <strong>able to evidence the TV work via P60s, P45s and HMRC summary of income to demonstrate consistency of earnings</strong> over the last two years. Plus we were <strong>able to use their current payslips to show the year to date earnings</strong>. We also had a copy of the current contract, therefore we were <strong>happy to proceed with the loan requested</strong>.</span></li>\n</ul>"
                }
              ],
              "settingsData": []
            }
          },
          {
            "contentTypeKey": "cc37be6c-af82-4a8f-bcfe-5dc50d675c4f",
            "udi": "umb://element/5176556fbad1434ab05b93ff99be19d5",
            "question": "Large loan applications",
            "answer": {
              "layout": {
                "Umbraco.BlockList": [
                  {
                    "contentUdi": "umb://element/c1806ec8fde94dc280087c756776d538"
                  }
                ]
              },
              "contentData": [
                {
                  "contentTypeKey": "dba6735d-7dc0-4fe4-b679-bb35d308181a",
                  "udi": "umb://element/c1806ec8fde94dc280087c756776d538",
                  "answer": "<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £963,000 at 90% LTV</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">Applicant one was an Analyst for a large financial firm with a <strong>basic salary of £110,000 plus annual bonus circa £110,000</strong>. Applicant two was a Marketing Manager on a <strong>spousal visa</strong>.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\"><strong>The loan was affordable on applicant one’s basic salary</strong> and <strong>using 50% of the latest year’s bonus over a 39 year term</strong>. Therefore we were happy to lend the amount requested.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £2,400,000 at 60% LTV</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The application was a <strong>like for like remortgage on an interest only basis</strong>. Applicant one’s basic <strong>salary was £240,000 and they received an annual bonus of £536,000</strong>.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">As <strong>the applicant had a financially dependent spouse and three children, we needed to use 75% of the bonus for the application</strong> to pass affordability. <strong>Due to the applicant’s track record of bonuses at a similar level in previous years</strong> we were happy to lend the amount required.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £1,800,000 at 75% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicant held a senior position in a large bank and was <strong>paid a large salary as well as bonuses</strong>. The size of loan they wanted wouldn’t have been possible using our standard loan terms.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">When reviewing the case we were happy to include the <strong>average of 100% of their bonuses for the previous two years</strong> as part of the total assessable income, even though the <strong>bonuses varied each year</strong>. This was due to the <strong>applicant’s track record of bonuses </strong>at a similar level in previous years, <strong>demonstrating a sustainable source of income</strong>. </span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"list-bullets -blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £1,249,500 at 85% LTV</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">One of the applicants has only<strong> recently become self employed; less than two years ago</strong>. Their company is in the same industry they had been previously employed in. With this employment history they wouldn’t have been able to secure the loan on standard terms.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">When reviewing the case they were able to provide <strong>evidence that the company was performing well</strong>, even though it was relatively new. This <strong>included one years’ finalised accounts and the latest year’s net profit after tax (NPAT) and salary</strong>. On standard terms we would normally require evidence of dividends being received.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">We therefore used <strong>one year’s finalised accounts and the latest year’s NPAT and salary</strong> for our income assessment to achieve the loan amount required.</span></li>\n</ul>"
                }
              ],
              "settingsData": []
            }
          },
          {
            "contentTypeKey": "cc37be6c-af82-4a8f-bcfe-5dc50d675c4f",
            "udi": "umb://element/95e210ce95f7481a86e6522647a3d8bb",
            "question": "Professional applicants",
            "answer": {
              "layout": {
                "Umbraco.BlockList": [
                  {
                    "contentUdi": "umb://element/7fe11dd7579345a4a486cfaca8bb4c16"
                  }
                ]
              },
              "contentData": [
                {
                  "contentTypeKey": "dba6735d-7dc0-4fe4-b679-bb35d308181a",
                  "udi": "umb://element/7fe11dd7579345a4a486cfaca8bb4c16",
                  "answer": "<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £1,800,000 at 75% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicant held a senior position in a large bank and was <strong>paid a large salary as well as bonuses</strong>. The size of loan they wanted wouldn’t have been possible using our standard loan terms.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">We were happy to include the <strong>average of 100% of their bonuses for the previous two years</strong> as part of the total assessable income, even though the <strong>bonuses varied each year</strong>. This was due to the <strong>applicant’s track record of bonuses </strong>at a similar level in previous years.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong> </strong><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £520,000 at 89% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">Applicant one had been a self employed dentist for two years. Applicant two was an employed scientist for four years. They had no dependents and a credit card payment of £65 per month.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">Applicant one’s first year’s <strong>income was impacted by Covid</strong> and therefore <strong>significantly lower than the latest year.</strong></span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">As the <strong>applicant could provide the last six remittances slips which when annualised would mean the current tax year will be significantly higher</strong>, we were <strong>happy to use the latest year in isolation.</strong></span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £500,000 at 50% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicant had been an <strong>employee of a limited liability partnership (LLP)</strong> for a number of years and around <strong>18 months ago became a self employed partner in the firm</strong>. The <strong>LLP was well established and profitable</strong>. On standard terms the applicant would need three years’ accounts to assess in order to apply.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">When reviewing the case we agreed to <strong>include the applicant’s profit share</strong> for our assessment as we received confirmation from the finance director of the previous and expected earnings along with a P60 to evidence the level of earnings before becoming an equity partner.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £335,000 at 81% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicant had <strong>qualified as a Barrister six months ago</strong> and had <strong>self employed and pupillage income. </strong></span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">We were able to <strong>use the certificate from Chambers</strong> to confirm income earnt along with anticipated future earnings, and therefore, <strong>used the latest year’s profit figure in isolation for our income assessment.</strong></span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for a loan of £245,000 at 90% LTV  </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">Sole applicant had been a <strong>self employed dentist for nine months</strong>. They were previously employed whilst completing their training. They had no dependents and no commitments.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">The applicant was purchasing a flat with a gifted deposit from parents overseas.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">As the applicant could provide remittance slips for the last nine months showing an upward trend, we were <strong>able to average and annualise the income</strong> and lend the loan required. </span></li>\n</ul>"
                }
              ],
              "settingsData": []
            }
          },
          {
            "contentTypeKey": "cc37be6c-af82-4a8f-bcfe-5dc50d675c4f",
            "udi": "umb://element/2c52863532cd4ae7a25ceea9d447d82d",
            "question": "Remortgage with Capital Raising ",
            "answer": {
              "layout": {
                "Umbraco.BlockList": [
                  {
                    "contentUdi": "umb://element/fd6e0f135ab842b5ae35745b6d4f1bac"
                  }
                ]
              },
              "contentData": [
                {
                  "contentTypeKey": "dba6735d-7dc0-4fe4-b679-bb35d308181a",
                  "udi": "umb://element/fd6e0f135ab842b5ae35745b6d4f1bac",
                  "answer": "<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>A</strong><strong>pplication for loan of £388,333 at 75% LTV </strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">Applicants were <strong>capital raising £179,838</strong> for home improvements, as they needed to adapt and extend their home due to disability. Prior to applying the applicants had obtained all planning consents, drawings and quotes for the work along with timescales.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">One applicant had <strong>only been a partner in a law firm for nine months</strong>. However they were previously an employee with the same firm and earning a similar level. We were able to get confirmation from the accountant of expected earnings and therefore we were happy to include their income as part of our assessment.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong><span class=\"-blue-text\">Application for loan of £1,275,000 at 85% LTV</span></strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">Applicants were <strong>capital raising £337,000</strong> for home improvements as they were building a two story extension. They had obtained all planning consents, drawings and quotes for the work along with timescales.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\"><strong>As an exception we agreed to lend at 50% interest only and 35% on repayment</strong> due to the high quality of the application, we also <strong>agreed to</strong> <strong>exceed our standard Loan to Value limits</strong>.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong style=\"color: #0000ff;\">Application for loan of £322,500 at 83% LTV</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">Applicants were <strong>capital raising £67,500</strong> for the deposit on a buy to let property.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\"><strong>We agreed not to deduct £1,417 per month school fees</strong> (payable for the next ten years) <strong>as a monthly outgoing for affordability</strong> as the applicants could evidence £180,000 in savings to cover these fees.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"-blue-text\"><strong>Application for loan of £1,314,495 at 75% LTV</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">Applicants were <strong>capital raising £208,562</strong> for home improvements on their residential property and to redeem their buy to let mortgage.</span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\">When reviewing the case we could see that one applicant had an <strong>undrawn Self Invested Personal Pension (SIPP) </strong>and was old enough to access this if needed. By providing us with evidence of the SIPP balance <strong>we were able to include this as part of the total assessable income.</strong></span></li>\n<li><span class=\"list-bullets\"><strong>We agreed to lend to age 75 with 60% on interest only basis and the remaining 15% on repayment</strong>.</span></li>\n</ul>"
                }
              ],
              "settingsData": []
            }
          },
          {
            "contentTypeKey": "cc37be6c-af82-4a8f-bcfe-5dc50d675c4f",
